For the last 2 weeks I’ve been trekking around Patagonia alone, experiencing vast wilderness that gave space for the mind to explore itself and be present in the moment with no other distractions. In general I prefer to travel and hike with others but this time has been special. 
Photo: taken during my last day on the 4 day Huemul Trek, near El Chaltén. The wind was howling with rain and I was leaning almost sideways into the wind to stay upright when thru that wild tempest of the elements broke the sun creating this rainbow. #patagonia 
One more month to go until I return to Peru for a 9 day Photography workshop. Come join me. Link in the bio.

Put me on a beach filled with penguins and I’ll be a happy guy. I love watching these short little guys waddle around with their flippers held out. Hope you enjoy the videos I shots with my phone. @chimuadventures

When was the last time that nature completely blew your mind? It can be on a big scale or on a micro scale but I’d love to hear. 
Feeling especially grateful for our beautiful little planet today and I’m continuing to do my best to cut one time use plastics out of my life. 
Thank you for your support.
Photo: Glow Worm Cave in New Zealand on the North Island. This is one of the experiences that blew my mind

I love Autumn but I never had thought of going south this time of year to experience it until a saw a photo a year or so ago of Patagonia with Fall leaves 🍂, so thank you for the inspiration unknown photographer and hope I can now do the same for some of you. 
I’m having a hard time picking a favorite photo. Is there one that rises above the others to you?
The leaves here in Patagonia are beginning to change colors giving this icy landscape a dash of reds and oranges.

Antarctica is done, but before going home, I had to make the short jump over to Patagonia. As I drove into El Chalten that sits below Mount Fitz Roy, the mountain was covered in clouds. I wasn’t surprised because I knew the area is notorious for wild weather and poor visibility but what I didn’t expect was that the next day, I’d see the Mount Fitz Roy Massif for the first time like this! That day was perfect with little to no wind. I walk 24 miles that day and today was also nice with another 14 miles covered. What I can say is that the area is living up to the hype and I’m feeling grateful to be here. Be sure to check out the stories that I’m going to try and post now. 
Also as a reminder. I have 2 more spots available in my Peru Workshop come this May 5-13 and I’d love to have you join. Follow the link in my bio for more details.

Hands down, my favorite bird on the planet is a penguin and of all the penguins the King Penguin is the most beautiful. During my recent trip to Antarctica, we had plans to go to South Georgia and see millions of these birds but weather prevented us from going there so we instead went to the Falkland Islands.  While there we found a few Kings rearing their chicks on a pristine white sand beach. @chimuadventures

It’s so much easier to see where I’m going in life because of my time in the mountains.
Location: Istwoot Ridge in the North Cascades of WA. This is a photo I took of myself using my tripod and phone connected to my camera to act as a remote. The mountain in the distance is Glacier Peak. 
6 more hours to go before we board the ship bound for Antartica, South Georgia, and the Falkland Islands. The cruise will last for 18 days and during those 18 days I won’t have any phone service and won’t be able to make post and stories. With that being said, I will be using my Garmin Explorer device to send updates and locations to my Facebook Page “ Jacob Moon Photography “ so that will be the place to follow my trip until I get back.

Anyone that tells you that you’re days of traveling and backpacking will be over once you have a baby is not telling you the truth. 
If you’d like to read some of the recent blogs that my wife wrote about our travels with our daughter, you can find them linked in her bio at @rebornbyadventure and if you’d like to see more photos from our family adventures and get adventure baby tips, follow our family account @moonmountainlife
Lastly, if you like podcast I just did an interview with a podcast “By Land” look them up and let me know what you thought about the interview.

Yosemite Mist against the indomitable walls of the Captain. 
I just landed in Buenos Aires, Argentine. I have a 30 hour lay over before continuing on to Ushuaia where I’ll hope on a 🚢 to go see Antarctica 🇦🇶!

Well, Im off and on my way to Antartica🇦🇶 and Patagonia🇦🇷. The trip of a life time and I know I should be feeling stoked out of my mind, but honestly.. leaving my family at home has me feeling really down at the moment. I know it will pass but being away for 5 weeks is along time in the life of an infant. I most likely won’t get to see my daughters first steps. She is so close to walking... At the same time, I have to be extremely grateful for all the time I’ve been able to she with her. 
I AM, deep down excited for the trip and to share the journey with all of you. While on the 18 day Antarctica Cruise, I won’t have service but I’ll do my best otherwise to share the trip. ✈️ First stop: Buenos Aires 🇦🇷 for a 1 day layover, then on to Ushuaia 🇦🇷 where things start getting really interesting 🚢🇦🇶 🤗

node.text: On the north island of New Zealand stands Mt Taranaki 8,200 feet above the surrounding farm land and Lake Mangamahoe (pictured). This was probably one of my favorite spots we stopped to cook dinner at while on a 2 month road trip with my wife and then 6 month old daughter just a few months ago. I don’t know if I’ll ever stop thinking about this place until I go back.
The most vivid and life changing moments in my life have never been achieved by staying in my comfort zone and taking the easiest road that has a known outcome.

Far and away the most common, now daily, question that I get is “what do you do for a living and how can you afford to travel and live the life that your living?” So I guess it’s time for another post to answer it. Well the first part of this question is really easy to answer. I am currently working as a full time photography and have been doing so for just over a year now. Before that I spent 7 years working as a full time Registered nurse in a hospital (so all the photo you see more then a year ago, I was working as a full time nurse, more or less 😉, to make those trips happen. )

Now for the second part of the question is harder to answer in a satisfactory way. This is because more often then not the questioners ideas of what is affordable travel and the life I’m  living don’t align with my reality and ideas, 
But the answer is really simple, We live within our means and, thus far we are healthy. This means we don’t have debt, we don’t eat out . We rarely ever spend more then $20 for a place to stay at night when traveling (most of the time we don’t pay anything), We own one old inexpensive vehicle. Our rent although more then we’d like is less then most places, We try to avoid buying things that we don’t need..... anyways I think you get the picture. 
The end result is that even though perhaps we don’t make a lot of money, we purposefully spend the money that we do have on chasing our dreams and our idea of a good life. 
Obviously there is a lot to explain in order to answer this question fully. If you’d like hear the full answer and also learn about being a photographer, social media and a lot more that contributes to over all answer, you should join me at one of my photography workshops or wait until I get around to writing a book some day, but until then I’ll do my best to answer as many follow up questions as I’ve got time for here. Once again and as always, thank you for your support. 
This photo was taken at a special place in Chiapas MX. Message me for the name of the place but if you go please take a garbage bag with you and pack out your trash and any other trash you find down there. Let keep it beautiful and urge others to do so also. Thank you.

Some of the best moments in my life have been some of the most simple ones. Striped of the things the “world” says we need to be happy and fully engaged in just being present in the moment.

Photo enjoying a quiet cup of coffee high in the New Zealand southern Alps with @Rebornbyadventure while our daughter slept in the tent behind us.
Captured what a Sony A7RII and 16-35 F/4 lens on a Gitzo Carbón Travel Tripod.

Join me for my photography workshop in Peru this May 5-13. Details in my bio.

Car Camping or Van Life? We have loved using our Gen 3 4Runner for all our road trips. I have a sleeping platform in the back and we used a tent when ever we found great places to camp while on road trips but now with our 10 month old daughter crawling, standing and soon walking, sleeping in the back of our 4Runner is pretty uncomfortable and having a vehicle that we can sleep in is necessary for our way of travel because places to tent camp are always as beautiful, free and convenient to get to so I think New Zealand ruined us and we are now heavily in favor of the van life and hope to be able to afford and built out a Sprinter Van this year.

We left Washington to find some sun but when we got to Havasupai in Arizona, we found our trip smack dab in the middle of one of the few storms Arizona has seen in months. As we drove to the trailhead my stoke level was maybe a 3/10. There was fresh snow everywhere, it was hand bubbling cold and the sun was covered by clouds. I honestly didn’t want to go, but the permits aren’t cheap so we went and once down in the canyon it was a different world. The weather was pleasant even during the night and when the sun came out it was shorts and T-shirt weather but weather aside, the location...😍. It surpassed all my expectation in beauty and is very unique. Coming in February for me was the right choice, despite the colder temps, because there was only 60ish/360 other people camping and it felt empty. Glad I got to go and experience this place with my wife ( @rebornbyadventure ) and now 9 month old daughter ( @moonmountainlife )

May 5-13 Peru Photography Workshop: still have spots available. Click on link in bio for details. It’s going to be epic

Instead of a blazing fireplace, I only had a candle.... so almost perfect.
Fun fact: no matter the temperature outside, a snow cave doesn’t get colder than just below freezing, and can get as warm as 48 degrees (from my experience) if built right.

Glowing a little brighter than stars, the glow worms of New Zealand are bucket list worthy to see but are difficult to photograph and the kind of camera that you have does matter. To take this photo (this is a single image with no photoshop) I used a Sony A7RII with the Sigma 20mm f/1.4 Lens (Canon Lens) and lens adapter. I put the camera on a tripod, set the focus manually, adjusted my setting to ISO 1000, f/1.4,  and shutter on Bulb at 140 seconds. Then I connected the camera to my phone using the Sony Camera app and set the timer to 5 seconds. Once in position, I hit the button on my phone and hid it, 5 seconds later the shutter opened and I stood still and marveled at the glow worms, when I was ready I flashed my head lamp around for about 1-2 seconds then turned it off. While standing there in darkness marveling at the glow worms, I listened to some music by Ludovico Einaudi and once the music reached a predetermined spot (140 seconds in) I quickly pulled out my photo and closed the shutter on camera via the app. Some people might think that standing there was hard to do and boring but not so. I absolutely love how long exposure photos make me hold perfectly still and taken in the experience completely. This room in the cave I dubbed the Nebula Room.
Location: I’ve given it before in previous glow worm post and won’t say it again.

Thank you everyone that responded to my post a few days ago asking about what social media can do to help protect our wild places. Listening to the seemingly endless stream of News about the attacks on our public’s land and wild places has been heart breaking and I’m trying to figure out what I can do and where I stand on issues.  One thing I’ve decided is that keeping places a secret is a mistake and ultimately could contribute to the the lose of places I love so much. Bears Ears National Monument and Grand Stair Case Escalate National Monument are prime examples of this but are not the only ones. Chances are you haven’t heard about these places and if you have it was likely during the last year or so as people tried to get the word out and gain support to protect them but ultimately, our efforts failed. Although spreading the word about places that few know about could bring crowds and careless people that litter those problems pale in comparison to what corporate greed that can lead to their demise. I don want to see our old growth forest being cut down, mines being established in pristine wilderness and rivers being polluted by factories. When the corporate $$$ can speak louder than the people we have a problem. These places when lost will not simple return to they way they were once the resources have been extracted in most cases. 
To start this apology, this photo that I am sharing is from the La Venta River in Chiapas Mexico. I’ve selfishly been quiet about it but I hope to walk the fine line in the future between bring awareness to an area while avoiding the pin pointing of specific spots. As I share more about this place and other in the future please Please PLEASE! take care of them, Don’t litter and add your voice to the fight to protect and preserve these places
Thank you 🙏

node.text:
During my last photography workshop to Peru, we did a trek around the Cordillera Huayhuash Mountains. On day 3 we arrived at Laguna Carhuacocha (pictured), made camp and after enjoying the evening around the lake, I check my star app (I was using sky safari) on my phone and noticed that the Milky Way was going to line up perfectly for doing some night photography at 4 am so we went to bed with our alarms set to 3:30am. Nights in the Peruvian Andes are crisp but when our alarms when off, we crawled out of our tents and were greeted by one of the clearest night sky I’ve ever seen with the core of the Milky Way lining up just about the Cordillera Huayhuash Mountains AND reflected perfectly in Laguna Carhuacocha. I could have asked for a more perfect place and conditions to teach night photography. 📷: Canon 6d with canon 24mm f/1.4 lens
On May 5-13th I will be returning  to Peru, this time in partnership with @flashpackerconnect, to host a photography workshop around the Cusco region and I’d love to have you join me. The price is all inclusive and covers everything from beginning to end of the 9 day workshop, all you have to do is get to Lima (airfare there is cheap) Join me. Link to details in my bio 👆and feel free to send me a message with any questions you might have.

What role do you believe social media should play in the fight to protect and preserve our public lands and wild places, if any? Do you do anything outside of social media, in the fight? I’d really be interested in hearing your thoughts. If you don’t believe they need help, I’d also love to hear from you.

One of the best half day hikes in the world without question. The Hooker Valley Track in New Zealand is 👌 so good (completely unobstructed views of massive Ice Falls, lakes with glaciers flowing into them, towering mountains, and an easy well maintained trail for all) I’ve never seen anything like it.
Today: Who woke up this morning to see the Super Blue Blood Moon and got skunked by clouds? 🤗 This guy.. sigh...

Knowledge and experience are the direct opposites of fear and as a new dad I was terrified on so many levels when Zoey came along. I’d heard all kinds of people telling me that “When the kid comes you won’t be able to do...(fill in the blank). It seemed that having a baby would be the end of our lives as we knew it but together with my wife we vowed that we’d never give up the outdoors. The outdoors for us isn’t just a place we go to recreate. It is so much more. There is a power out there in the clean air and natural beauty, that I find hard to describe but we knew that we wanted our daughter to have it, so we began learning. With all of our previous experiences and knowledge at our backs, we started by going car camping. It was the perfect way to experience the outdoors in a safe and controlled way, for us. With the car loaded with everything we had thought the baby would ever need, we began learning what she really needed and what we could leave behind. From there, trip after trip, we learned what we needed to know so that when we ventured into the backcountry we were prepared and the rest is history. 
If you’d like to see more post and tips with my daughter and our adventures, you can follow along at @moonmountainlife and my wife’s account @rebornbyadventure 
Also I really enjoy following @bornwildproject to find others that are getting there kids out for inspiration #iwasbornwild

I love sharing myself and work with anyone that cares listen and look. With that being said, do you have any questions for me? What could I tell you, that might bring you some inspiration?

Edited with Adobe Lightroom 🙋 @rebornbyadventure

Focused and living in the Here, the Now. Disconnected from the rest of world. Connected only to the natural world surrounding me. The passing of time marked by the rhythm of my heart, the rod and movement of water and sun.  @alpacka_raft @tenkararodco

After spending 2 months in New Zealand with little to no access to the internet and now being home with blazing fast internet at my figure tips, I just realized how much that wealth of information makes me lose focus on my life. Being reintroduced to the internet in such a brutally abrupt way is what I would imagine being reintroduce to a drug would feel like after going without it for a long period of time. Focus and clarity of life and it’s tasks is now all a blur with my attention jumping from one thing to another as I work, plan,read new, learning new skills, do research, respond to emails, see what others are doing etc... perhaps before I left I had some time management skills and control on my mind but those parts of my mind seem to have weakened and now I find myself longing to escapes back to the mountains where the internet doesn’t exist and my life just is.... but I’ve to got get some work done first, so back to work and exercising control of my attention.

Winter is one of my favorite times of the year to go camping. I love that the locations you can camp are almost limitless. I love the look of the winter coats the mountain wear. I love how the stars shine on a cold winter night and light up the white landscape. I love building the endless possibilities of things I can build in the snow(caves, tables, chairs, etc..) I don’t know... I just love it. I might be a special kind of crazy 😜 
How many of you have ever camped in the winter or winter like conditions and  it is something that you’d like to learn and do? I’m happy to answer specific  questions if you have any.

3/3 My favorite #goatworthy experience from NZ would have to be our time spent in Mount Cook National Park on the South Island. @rebornbyadventure and I both agree that the Hooker Valley hike is one of our all time favorite half day hikes and our time spent camping next to the Muller Hut was our favorite camp site in NZ.  What made this area so unique and beautiful was the glaciers. I’ve never see ice falls and massive glaciers flowing into lakes as such a low altitude and within easy walking distance from a trailhead. It was second to non. The weather was perfect and the views we’re our favorite in New Zealand. 
#chaseyourgoat @backcountry

2/3 My 2nd favorite #GOATworthy experience from NZ was wondering around in dark places lit by glow worms. 
Towards the end of our trip, we returned to the North Island and had a few days with a forecast that called for rain and strong winds. Instead of battling the elements outside, I decided to go underground. We drove a few hour north of Auckland thru pouring rain and gale force winds to this cave. Once inside the wind and rain were gone and once my eye adjusted to the darkness, I looked up to see what appeared to be the galaxy 🌌 in the night sky. In actuality it was thousands and thousands of little inch long glow worms that cover the ceiling of the cave. I don’t have words to describe my wonder let’s just saw over the 2 days that it was pouring rain outside, I spent a total of 16 hour down here looking at 🐛 and trying to capture the experience. The second photo shows the worms up close.
@backcountry #chaseyourgoat 🐛 = 🌌 =🐐 (WARNING: Flash Floods can and do occur in cave during rain storms. People have died in the particular cave in such an event.)
Location: I found this place in my research easy enough and I’ve mentioned the location before, so I’ll leave it at that but there are many places throughout NZ to see the glow worms.

1/3 We are home but NZ will never be forgotten. So many good memories to be shared but over the next 3 post I’ll be sharing my top 3 favorite #goatworthy moments from our trip. (GOAT=Greatest Of All Time) 
First, was our over nighter up at Alex Knob over looking the Franz Josef Glacier, West Coast, South Island. Not only was our camp sight just 👌🏻 but we actually almost left and hiked down because the weather was terrible and didn’t look like it was going to improve. We hiked up early in the day and set up camp in a white out and light rain. We decided that if things didn’t improve by X time, we’d pack up and hike out because the weather forecast for the next day was terrible. We waited and waited, the time came, things still looked terrible, so we actually packed up all our things and walked back down the trail about a km before I started to notice some clearing. We decided to wait 10 minutes, then undecided we gave it another 10 mins, then hopeful, 10 more minutes and in a blink of an eye, it went from white out to this 😅😃🎊🎉🎊. We hiked back to our tent site, set up camp (pictured) and enjoyed the absolutely stunning experience of being here.  The next day, although very dark and cloudy, it didn’t rain until we reached our car!😅. That’s what I call the perfect weather window for a perfect trip. @backcountry #chaseyourgoat
Looking back at the roads we’ve driven and the memories we now have there... New Zealand was perfect for our little family.  In a few hours we will board our flight home. #goodbyenewzealand

Taco the Van has been sold. As hard it was to watch him drive away with his new owners, I could help but smile knowing that although our adventure here is over, his will continue with them and then with the next owners and the next and the next and on and on. May you never die Taco ✊️#MayTacoNeverDie #ThankTheTaco

node.text:
Below the surface of the earth is an entirely different world. One that I mostly just forget about and have spent very little time in but in my search to see glow worms, I found this cave. What I found was not just a few glow worms but a room that is referred to as “The Galaxy Room” and another spot that few have seen that I named “The Nebula” ( those photos will come later ). The experience left me in awe and instead of a quick visit we camped out there for 2 days while I spent a total of 16 hours down in that world exploring and marveling at these unique worms 🐛. Location: The name to this place was mentioned in my previous glow worm photo caption and stories. That’s all I’ll say
Camera: Sony A7RII, Sigma 20mm 1.4 lens with adapter, connected to and controlled by my iPhone via WiFi
Settings: f/1.4, shutter bulb(103 seconds) ISO 1600, 
Music playing while holding still for the photo Ludovico Einaudi - Nuvole Bianche 👌🏻

Do you read captions? If so what do you like to read in the captions? Stories? Quotes? Clever one liners? Descriptions? Tips/Hints? Photography stuff, etc... Also I’m sorry for the poor writing/spelling in my captions. My brain and fingers don’t communicate very well. I try but mistakes always get thru into my captions😒 sorry about that. 
Today’s captions: Lupines, Glacier Blue Water of Lake Tekapo, and the Southern Alps of New Zealand. Taken with my Sony A7RII and a 16-35 f/4 lens (my general go to lens)

One of my big bucket list things to see in New Zealand was the glow worms 🐛. If you’ve been following my stories, you will know that we visited Waitomo Caves to see the glow worms there, and I found them disappointing. They are very touristy, expensive (luckily we have a big discount), terrible for photography due to time constraints or photography is just not allowed there. Despite the disappointment, I did get to see some glow worms and they set my mind alight. They are just pure magic and I had to see more, so I asked for location suggestions on my IG Story. The first stop I made from the suggestions was here at McLaren Falls Park near Tauranga, NZ. It was beautiful there. The park itself was beautiful, with excellent camping. At night along the little stream running through a dark jungle section of the park glow worms lite up in the thousands giving light to the dark jungle. I was down there marveling at their beauty for 3 hours and didn’t see another person the whole time. Then last night I spent 5 hours down in the Waipu Cave, and the photos from there will blow your mind but for now I want you to appreciate these.  I’ll share the other photos with you a little later. 😏. Today is a rainy day so I think I just have to go spend more time  in the Waipu caves . I ❤️ glow worms 🐛.

I’ve enjoy all the twist and turns in the road that has taken me to all the places I’ve been and I’m stoked to see where it continues to take me.
One year ago today I decided it was time to quite my job as a nurse (which I did enjoy) and my love for photography full time. 2 weeks later that reality came true and 1 year later (today) I’m still going 😁. Trying to figure out how to put this life together and make it work has been like putting together a massive puzzle. While I’m still trying to find some of the pieces, I now have a good idea what the puzzle should look like when I’m done. Hopefully in 2018 I’ll finally find those missing pieces. Happy New Year everyone. Don’t be afraid of pursuing the New this year.
A night under the stars above the Franz Josef Glacier one the West Coast of NZ’s South Island. The end.... cursed captions..
The way is shut so we couldn’t find the door but we could feel their eyes watching us as while walking the Paths of The Dead 💀. 🙋@rebornbyadventure #loveNerding

(Rare post of myself and here to answer questions. Hope you enjoy) Up valleys, over mountains, down rivers and across lakes this is how I roll and the gear that I use is very important. Over years I’ve found what works best for me and I am happy to answer questions that you might have on this post (when my internet connection allows). As the year comes to end I just want to give a big thank you to @eddiebauer for all the support they gave me this year to help me bring you all some rad adventures and hopefully inspiration. Over the past 2 years I’ve use a lot of their gear and clothing so I want to mention a few pieces that I particularly love here. 1. Guide Pro Hiking Pants. favorite hiking pants I’ve ever owned. 2. The EverTherm Down Jacket. To date my favorite lightweight puffy and finally 3. Eddie Bauer’s Favorite Flannel shirt, which has also become my favorite. Their is more but these are my all time favorites come with me nearly everywhere.
Photo: This photo was taken atop Gillespie Pass in Mount Aspiring National Park, NZ with my 7 month old daughter, Zoey, and @rebornbyadventure (taking the photo). Our plan on this 4 day trip was to stay in huts and float down the Siberia and Wilkins Rivers to exits so beyond my normal camera equipment, gear and food I was also packing a 2 person packraft, life jackets, paddle and Tenkara Fishing equipement. #liveyouradventure #ebcontributor

Our first ever tropical Christmas and Zoeys first Christmas. We did a very leisurely 3 1/2 days paddles down the Abel Tasman Coast of New Zealand with our @alpacka_raft Although I am very much a mountain guy and missed having a white Christmas, we all enjoyed the change of pace and decided that it is a must do while in New Zealand. Photo: (1) Having lunch on the beach with a seal, middle right of the photo, on Christmas Eve (2) Christmas Day hanging out of the beach (3) A beautiful Little Blue Penguin that we saw on our way out around Adel Island. The Blue Penguin is the smallest species in the world at just over a foot in height and under 3 lbs.

Yesterday was our last day in the southern Alps of New Zealand. Today we are taking care of things, driving and getting ready to take our @alpacka_raft leisurely down the the Abel Tasman Coast over the next few day (including Christmas) so from the Moon’s I wanted to wish you all a Merry Christmas!!! Thank you all so much for your support and love that you send with you’re comments and likes. Although I have been terrible at responding to comments while down here, I read them all and value them. To follow more of our adventure be sure to follow my wife’s account also @rebornbyadventure

Watching Plane and Helicopter flying around the southern alps, cruise ships make their way into the Milford Sound and vehicles drive down the glacial craves valleys below, I was the only person on this mountain far above Gertrude Saddle silently enjoying this view of Fjordlands National Park with the Milford Sound perfectly centered down the valley

Once an old forgotten fence post, now perhaps the most photographed tree in the world? Not sure but today we will be going over Haast Pass to the West Coast and it will be our last time in the town of Wanaka. We spent several long afternoons here on the beaches of Lake Wanaka in town relaxing and enjoying the absence of sand flies. I love it here.
